### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

common

### Description

I was working on a project involving rendering of markdown. We were parsing and sanitizing the generated html, and as part of that sanitization, it would rewrite element ids to prevent dom-clobbering attacks. 

Specifically, if a generated html element is as follows
`<h2 id="some-heading-id">`
then the output would be
`<h2 id="user-content-some-heading-id">`


Obviously, this would break links, because `demo.com/some-document#some-heading-id` would no longer work, and we would have to use `demo.com/some-document#user-content-some-heading-id` instead. Except, now the links don't look like what my client would want for SEO and it would break existing links.

So to work around this, I modified the behaviour of ViewportScroller (see [customize-viewport-scroller.ts](#customize-viewport-scroller.ts)).


Now, the thing to note is that I had to:
- copy over the implementation of `findAnchorFromDocument` from the `@angular/common` library
- provide type information for `BrowserViewportScroller` 

<details id="customize-viewport-scroller.ts">
<summary>
 <strong>customize-viewport-scroller.ts</strong>
</summary>
<p>

```ts
import { ViewportScroller } from '@angular/common';
import { afterNextRender, inject, INJECTOR, provideAppInitializer } from '@angular/core';
import { isServer } from '../utilities/platform-type';


export function customizeProvidedViewportScroller() {
  return provideAppInitializer(() => {
    if (isServer()) return;

    const injector = inject(INJECTOR);

    type BrowserViewportScroller = ViewportScroller & {
      document: Document,
      scrollToElement: (element: HTMLElement, options?: ScrollOptions) => void;
    };

    const scroller = inject(ViewportScroller) as BrowserViewportScroller;

    function scrollToAnchor(this: BrowserViewportScroller, target: string, options?: ScrollOptions) {
      const elSelected = findAnchorFromDocument(this.document, target);

      if (elSelected) {
        this.scrollToElement(elSelected, options);
        elSelected.focus();
      }
      else {
        if (target.startsWith('user-content-')) {
          afterNextRender(() => {
            this.scrollToAnchor(target, options);
          }, { injector });
        }
        else {
          target = `user-content-${target}`;
          this.scrollToAnchor(target, options);
        }
      }
    }

    scroller.scrollToAnchor = scrollToAnchor.bind(scroller);
  });
}

function findAnchorFromDocument(document: Document, target: string) {
  const documentResult = document.getElementById(target) || document.getElementsByName(target)[0];
  if (documentResult) {
    return documentResult;
  }
  // `getElementById` and `getElementsByName` won't pierce through the shadow DOM so we
  // have to traverse the DOM manually and do the lookup through the shadow roots.
  if (typeof document.createTreeWalker === 'function' &&
    document.body &&
    typeof document.body.attachShadow === 'function') {
    const treeWalker = document.createTreeWalker(document.body, NodeFilter.SHOW_ELEMENT);
    let currentNode: Node | null = treeWalker.currentNode;
    while (currentNode) {
      const shadowRoot = (currentNode as Element).shadowRoot;
      if (shadowRoot) {
        // Note that `ShadowRoot` doesn't support `getElementsByName`
        // so we have to fall back to `querySelector`.
        const result = shadowRoot.getElementById(target) || shadowRoot.querySelector(`[name="${target}"]`);
        if (result) {
          return result;
        }
      }
      currentNode = treeWalker.nextNode();
    }
  }
  return null;
}
```

</p>
</details> 




### Proposed solution

the above will be a pain to maintain, because they may go out of sync as angular updates
- if you expose `findAnchorFromDocument` as a utility, then I can just import it and not have to maintain a user-land copy
- if you expose `BrowserViewportScroller` I can do an `if (scroller instanceof BrowserViewportScroller) { }` and remove my type declarations, or even better - I could even simply extend and override the class instead of doing function binding

### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

core

### Description

When https://github.com/tc39/proposal-explicit-resource-management has reached a sufficiently stable state for Angluar, please consider defining the `Symbol.dispose` (or its async counterpart) on the function returned by `PendingTasks.prototype.add()` method.

That would allow automatic cleanup of task like so:

```typescript
private readonly pendingTasks = inject(PendingTasks);
function foo() {
  // should this be `await using`?
  using _ = this.pendingTasks.add();
  ...
}
```

### Proposed solution

 ```typescript
  /**
   * Adds a new task that should block application's stability.
   * @returns A cleanup function that removes a task when called.
   */
  add(): () => void {
    const taskId = this.internalPendingTasks.add();
    const cleanup = () => {
      if (!this.internalPendingTasks.has(taskId)) {
        // This pending task has already been cleared.
        return;
      }
      // Notifying the scheduler will hold application stability open until the next tick.
      this.scheduler.notify(NotificationSource.PendingTaskRemoved);
      this.internalPendingTasks.remove(taskId);
    };
    cleanup[Symbol.dispose] = cleanup;
    return cleanup;
  }
```

### Alternatives considered

Will the cleanup have to be async? I don't thought that through.

### Which @angular/* package(s) are the source of the bug?

common

### Is this a regression?

No

### Description

This came up when testing an authentication http interceptor.
`auth.interceptor.ts`
```typescript
export const authInterceptor: HttpInterceptorFn = (req, next) => {
  return next(req).pipe(
    catchError((err, caught) => {
      if (err instanceof HttpErrorResponse && err.status === 401 && new URL(err.url).pathname !== '/api/logon') {
        return doLogonAndRetry(err, caught);
      }
      throw err;
    })
  );
};
```
Even if just the path specified when the request was made, when a 401 response comes back from the server `err.url` contains a full URL e.g. `https://angular.example/api/logon`. So the above code works with a service like:
`auth.service.ts`
```typescript 
@Injectable({providedIn: 'root'})
export class AuthService {
  private readonly http = inject(HttpClient);
  logon(username: string, password: string) {
    return this.http.post('/api/logon', {username, password});
  }
  validateSession(username: string, password: string) {
    return this.http.get('/api/whoami');
  }
}
```
However in a test using the HttpTestingController e.g.  
`auth.interceptor.spec.ts`
```typescript
it('should not intercept logon requests') {
  const http = TestBed.inject(HttpTestingController);
  const authService = TestBed.inject(AuthService);
  let receivedError: unknown;
  authService.logon('user', 'pass').subscribe({
    error: (error) => receivedError = error;
  });
  const req = controller.expectOne('/api/logon');
  req.flush({}, {status: 401, statusText: 'Unauthorized'});
  expect(receivedError).toBeInstanceOf(HttpErrorResponse);
  if (receivedError instanceof HttpErrorResponse) {
    expect(receivedError.status).toBe(401);
    expect(receivedError.statusText).toBe('Unauthorized');
  }
});
```
Instead `receivedError` is "TypeError: Failed to construct 'URL': Invalid URL". This is because `err.url` only contains the string `/logon`.  
I would expect HttpTestingController to emulate the behavior of connecting to an actual server as much as possible and so would expect the path to be expanded in to a full URL.  
This also means I cannot use existing services to test the interceptor in this case.

